<p>
    Let <m>g_n(x) = x^n</m> on the interval <m>[0,1]</m>. If <m>0\leq x &lt; 1</m> then <m>x^n \to 0</m> as <m>n \to \infty</m>, but if <m>x=1</m> then <m>x^n \to 1</m> as <m>x \to \infty</m>.
</p>

<p>
    Thus <m>g_n(x)</m> converges pointwise to the piecewise function
    <md>
        g(x) = \begin{cases} 
      \hfill 0 \amp \text{ if $ 0 \leq x &lt; 1$} \\
      \hfill  1 \hfill \amp \text{ if $x = 1$} \\
  \end{cases}
    </md>
    
</p>

<p>
    Note that this example is a sequence of continuous functions that converge to a function which is discontinuous at <m>1</m>.
</p>

